record.title: firm
record.detail: Celebrating the centenary of 1888, this arresting allegorical figure represents the colony of New South Wales and, more broadly, Australia. Placed on the southern staircase at Sydney Town Hall, she is replete with national icons: ram's horns for the wool industry, miner's lamp for mineral wealth, trident for maritime power, and the stars of the Southern Cross with the small fifth star on her forehead. The floral decoration is Australian wild flowers with waratahs predominating. The work was designed by Lucien Henry and made by Goodlet & Smith in Sydney in 1889.

record.title: produced
record.detail: Some of the finest stained glass windows in Australia were designed by Henry to celebrate the centenary of the founding of Sydney in 1788. His allegorical work symbolised the prosperity, wealth and authority of the colony and he pioneered the use f native flora in the decorative arts. Waratahs, Stenocarpus (firewheel) and Lambertia (mountain devil) feature in the outer frame.
